Okay, this isn't something I'm super familiar with, but from a glance at the code I'd probably bet the exception initially gets thrown from the call to `GetStreams()`

In your current build of PowerShell, you'll need to trigger the exception and then check `$error[0].Exception.GetType().FullName` -- that's probably the exception type you should target in the code.

I would probably recommend moving the `GetStreams()` call to before loop and store the result in a variable; that way, you can just have the try/catch around the GetStreams() call itself and not the entire loop.

Something similar to this pattern would most likely be effective:

```csharp
try
{
    var alternateStreams = AlternateDataStreamUtilities.GetStreams(result.FullName);
}
catch (Exception e) // replace Exception with the specific exception type you found earlier
{
    // you can probably reuse the WriteError() code from after the foreach loop here
    // though you'll need to locate the error string in the `*.resx` file (the name should match the class name, "FileSystemProviderStrings")
    // and add a new format string to reference so you can add in the `e.Message` from the caught exception here
    WriteError( ... );

    // finally just `return` from the method since we've already written an error and know there are no streams
    // that we can use for the foreach loop
    return;
}


foreach (AlternateStreamData stream in alternateStreams) {
    // ... (rest of the existing code in the loop etc)
```
Hopefully that makes some sense.

